{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16455"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16455"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.06,0.09,0.56,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75117"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9146"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75117"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe blood-brain barrier is a specialised structure that maintains central nervous system homeostasis by controlling substance movement between blood and brain tissue. Multiple cell types work together to maintain this barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cells plays the primary role in regulating both inflammatory cytokines and blood-brain barrier permeability?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Microglia","Endothelial cells","Oligodendrocytes","Astrocytes","Pericytes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAstrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are strategically positioned to regulate both blood-brain barrier integrity and inflammatory responses in the central nervous system. They achieve this through:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExtending end-feet processes that surround blood vessels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESecreting factors that maintain endothelial tight junctions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProducing pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECoordinating responses with other cells in the neurovascular unit\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other cells have different primary functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroglia\u003C/strong\u003E are the brain\u0027s resident immune cells but have less direct effect on barrier integrity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E form the physical barrier but do not primarily regulate inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOligodendrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E primarily produce myelin and do not significantly influence barrier function\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericytes\u003C/strong\u003E provide structural support to blood vessels but have limited influence on cytokine production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThrough their unique position and functions, astrocytes serve as master regulators of both barrier integrity and neuroinflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Astrocytes are key regulators of blood-brain barrier integrity through their end-feet processes and release of regulatory molecules.","Astrocytes produce both pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines that modulate neuroinflammation.","The blood-brain barrier consists of specialised endothelial cells, astrocytes, pericytes and basement membrane working together as a neurovascular unit."],"references":["Pan W, Stone KP, Hsuchou H, Manda VK, Zhang Y, Kastin AJ. Cytokine signaling modulates blood-brain barrier function. Curr Pharm Des. 2011 Nov;17(33):3729-40. doi: 10.2174/138161211798220918. PMID: 21834767; PMCID: PMC3939622.","Yarlagadda A, Alfson E, Clayton AH. The blood brain barrier and the role of cytokines in neuropsychiatry. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2009 Nov;6(11):18-22. PMID: 20049146; PMCID: PMC2801483.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16455"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T23:02:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:03:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9146"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75117"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":nul